    Tutorial: Deleting a Neighborhood Road Tile with a Hex Editor

    @criquette-was-here​ discovered how to move individual road tiles using SimPe.  SimPE’s editor unfortunately doesn’t allow individual road tiles to be added or deleted.  However, it is possible to do this with SimPE plus a hex editor.  It’s not very user friendly, so I’m working on a program to automate the process, and I’d strongly recommend you practice a few times on a throwaway neighborhood first.  But if you want to delete a road tile, here’s how it goes:

    The first thing you need to do is open up the Neighborhood Terrain resource in SimPE.  Find the road tile you want to delete – you’ll need to already know how to find it – and write down its Y value first, then its X value second, then its texture value third.  (Skip the Z value; we don’t need it.)  Write down the total number of road tiles, too (you can see that on the Road Tiles dropdown).

    Swap over to the Converter tab and type the number of road tiles into the second blank box (it may or may not say “Decimal” depending on which version of SimPE you’re using).  Copy down the last four digits of the number in the top line (in this case, 0186).

    While you’re in SimPE, right-click on the Neighborhood Terrain resource line and choose Extract.  Save it somewhere you’ll be able to easily find it later, such as your downloads folder.

    Next, you’ll need to convert the Y value and then the X value you wrote down into floating point numbers.  I’m using this converter.  Make sure you check single precision and then raw hexadecimal, and copy the hexadecimal floating point number it gives you.

    Take that number – e.g., 44584000 – and separate it into blocks of two digits each, like 44 58 40 00.  Now write in the blocks backwards: 00 40 58 44.  Do the same for the second hexadecimal number and for the total number of road tiles.

    For the next step, you’ll need a hex editor such as HxD.  Open up the file you extracted from SimPe.  You’ll see a whole lot of gibberish – don’t panic!  We already know exactly which numbers we need to find in this mess.

    Go up to Search > Find at the top, and type first 02, then the backwards  Y-value you wrote down, then the backwards X-value you wrote down.  Hit OK.

    Once it finds that string of numbers, hit shift+right arrow to keep highlighting until you get to the texture number a few lines later.

    Now carefully count out eleven more two-digit blocks.  If you’ve done it right, the next non-highlighted number should be 02.  Go ahead and hit the Delete key.  That series of numbers we just got rid of is what one individual road tile looks like in the .package file before SimPE cleans it up for us.

    Now, go to Search again.  This time, make sure you’re searching backwards.  Type in the backwards hexadecimal number for the total number of road tiles.

    Go back to SimPe and use its converter to convert one less than the current number (that is, we’ve already converted 390, so convert 389 and then write down/reverse the new hexadecimal number it gives you).

    Now swap back to HxD, delete the old road tile number, and type in the new one in its place.  Save the file.

    Go back to SimPE.  Right-click on the Neighborhood Terrain resource and replace it with the file you edited.  It’ll ask you whether to reload – go ahead and hit Yes.  If you get an error message, then something’s gone wrong, you must exit without saving, and you’ll have to start over from step one (but, since you didn’t save, your neighborhood should be safe); but if it loads correctly, then save, quit, and load up the game.

    Your unwanted road tile should now be gone.
